<div id="review_3342164508" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3342164508" />
    <a title="Jake Bornheimer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5838859-jake-bornheimer"><img alt="Jake Bornheimer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604460177p2/5838859.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3342164508?book_show_action=true">Jun 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jake Bornheimer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jake Bornheimer" href="/user/show/5838859-jake-bornheimer">Jake Bornheimer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/53434718-philobiblon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5838859-jake-bornheimer?shelf=in-collection">in-collection</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5838859-jake-bornheimer?shelf=books-on-books">books-on-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3342164508" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12528628745234946210">A book about the love of books from the 1300s. Written by the then Bishop of Durham and an alumnus of Oxford. While it was chiefly written to encourage other clergymen to respect, collect, and use books, it has great chapters on the care of books and of lending. In fact, Richard briefly discusses how librarianship worked at Oxford in the 14th century, which I found fascinating. It does contain a measure of religious guff, though said guff is pretty lyrical and enjoyable to read. I&apos;ll say, He doe</span>
  <span id="freeText12528628745234946210" style="display:none">A book about the love of books from the 1300s. Written by the then Bishop of Durham and an alumnus of Oxford. While it was chiefly written to encourage other clergymen to respect, collect, and use books, it has great chapters on the care of books and of lending. In fact, Richard briefly discusses how librarianship worked at Oxford in the 14th century, which I found fascinating. It does contain a measure of religious guff, though said guff is pretty lyrical and enjoyable to read. I'll say, He does seem particularly taken with Minerva (which is one of my favourite things to see in religious works: when Christians have an obsession with various pagan gods).</span>
  <a data-text-id="12528628745234946210" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
